The Federal Government has commissioned the Eastern zonal office of the Nigeria Maritime Administration and Safety Agency (NIMASA) in Port Harcourt, Rivers State capital The hospital was built to tackle rising cases of illnesses amongst seafarers in the region. Minister of Transportation, Mu’azu Sambo, who performed the inauguration on behalf of the Federal Government, also donated a building to the Centre of Logistics and Transportation Studies of the University of Port Harcourt for the purpose of enhancing maritime education in Rivers and its environs. Sambo said the building was the second largest in the country, saying it would enhance efficiency in delivering the core mandate of the agency. Represented by the ministry’s Permanent Secretary, Magdalene Ajani, he advised staff to double their efforts in their enforcement and monitoring of shipping activities across the Eastern zone of the country. The minister states that the new office, named after Mrs. Margaret Onyema-Orakwusi, a bigwig in the maritime sector, “is a property that has been purchased by NIMASA following the Federal Executive Council (FEC)’s approval. “It is for injured or ill seafarers in this region who are evacuated from the vessels and brought in here for treatment and it will serve as a clinic for the staff in the eastern zone. “Also, in the University of Port Harcourt, the agency had commissioned a building it donated for the use of a maritime institute in the university, he said.”